english:
  title: Record of a Journey Through Jirisan Mountain
  author: Lee Yuk
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Jirisan, also known as Duryu Mountain, stands majestically at the crossroads between Yeongnam and Honam, its height and breadth spanning hundreds of miles beyond reckoning. Encircling the mountain are one pastoral district, one provincial seat, two counties, five prefectures, and four dependent towns: to the east lie Jinju and Danseong; to the south, Kunyang, Hadong, Salcheon, Jeongryangm Hwagae, and Algyang; to the west, Namwon, Gurye, and Gwangyang; to the north, Hamyang and Saneum.

    Two peaks crown the mountain: to the east rises Cheonwang Peak, to the west Banya Peak, separated by more than a hundred li and perpetually veiled in clouds. Descending westward from Cheonwang, one encounters Hyungjeok Temple, and some fifty li further west, Gaseop Terrace, with Yeongsin Temple to its south. Descending another twenty li westward lies a vast, open plain—level and fertile, stretching some six or seven li in all directions. Here ancient cypress trees reach toward heaven, their fallen needles deep as ankles, and from the center, gazing in all directions, one perceives no boundary, as though standing in an endless prairie. Following a stream southward, one passes three temples: Uisin, Sinheung, and Ssanggye. Twenty li west of Uisin stands Chilbul Temple; crossing a ridge eastward from Ssanggye appears Bulil Hermitage. Countless other renowned temples and venerable monasteries dot the slopes, yet those perched upon the mountain's highest reaches—Hyungjeok and a few others—are roofed only with wooden shingles and shelter no monks, save Yeongsin Temple, which bears tile, though its inhabitants number scarce one or two. The mountain's towering isolation permits only the highest practitioners to dwell in such places.

    Waters spring from small fountains near Yeongsin Temple; by Shinheung they have become a mighty river flowing into the Seomjin, called the Hwagae Valley Stream. Descending eastward from Cheonwang, one finds Cheonbul Hermitage and Beopgye Temple. Climbing slightly north from Cheonbul, a small grotto opens eastward toward the great sea, westward shouldering Cheonwang Peak, possessed of extraordinary clarity and known as the Hermitage of the Rock Dharma Master. Two water courses converge at Salcheon—one from before Hyungjeok, one below Beopgye—joining into one and flowing into the lower reaches of Somnam Stream, circling Jinju and flowing eastward, called the Cheongcheon River. The Somnam waters from the north turn eastward until reaching Danseong County, where they bend westward again. Twenty-odd li from Salcheon village stands Poan Temple; the area within Salcheon village is called Inner Mountain, beyond is called Outer Mountain.

    Climbing directly from Poan Temple with swift ascent takes a day and a half to reach Cheonwang Peak. Yet the stone cliffs rise formidably steep; no clear path winds through. Ancient zelkova and cypress trees cloak the sky; below, dense mountain bamboo fills the undergrowth. Dead timber spans across thousand-foot precipices, moss crumbles and falls, and from the cloud's edge distant springs cascade through the space between cliffs, pouring into unmeasured depths. One cannot advance without turning one's heel; one cannot retreat and see behind. Only by felling dozens of trees does one glimpse a fraction of sky. Those devoted to such trials often gather stones and place them upon rocks to mark the way.

    In the ravines, ice and snow persist through summer unmelted—frost begins in the sixth month, snow in the seventh, great ice locks in the eighth. By early winter, snow fills the valleys completely level, impassable for human travel. Thus those dwelling on the mountain enter in autumn and descend only in late spring of the following year. Sometimes the lower slopes roar with thunder and torrential rain, while the summit remains clear and cloudless—for the mountain rises near to heaven itself, and its climate naturally differs utterly from the plains below.

    Generally, the lower mountain abounds in persimmon and chestnut trees; climbing higher, only zelkova appears; beyond the zelkova, fir and cypress predominate, though half stand withered and dead, their green and white intermingled like a painting. At the summit grows only azalea, its wood no taller than a man's arm. All manner of precious mountain herbs and exotic fruits flourish here more abundantly than upon other peaks, and dozens of settlements near the mountain all share in their bounty.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Jirisan (Jirisan) is Korea's largest mountain, straddling three provinces. It remains one of the most important Buddhist pilgrimage sites in Korea.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'thousand-foot precipices' reflect the dramatic terrain characteristic of Jirisan's inner peaks.
  - key: ''
    value: The observation about seasonal weather patterns reflects the mountain's actual meteorological distinctiveness due to its elevation and isolation.
